RISK MANAGEMENT PLAN UPDATE
EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

A Risk Management Plan has been implemented at ARKEMA¿s Carrollton production facility for the reduction of accidental releases of hazardous materials.  This Risk Management Plan summarizes the management, administrative, procedural, and technological controls that work together to minimize the risk to the community of hazardous chemical releases.  The Plan summary is organized to correspond with specific EPA RMP definitions and requirements, including:

¿ Introduction;
¿ ARKEMA policies to protect health, environment, and safety;
¿ Facility identification and regulated substances covered processes;
¿ Hazard Assessment;
¿ Prevention Program;
¿ Five year accident history;
¿ Emergency Response Plan;
¿ Planned changes to improve safety.

Risk management and safety have been important concerns at ARKEMA for many years; this RMP formalizes and documents these activities.  ARKEMA is committed to conducting its operations in a safe, responsible manner and to reducing risks to health and the environment.  

This commitment to health, environment, and safety (HES) starts with the CEO.  Senior management routinely dedicates time to review HES matters, including safety.  This emphasis on safety is carried through to the facility level, where plant personnel regularly review safety performance, take corrective actions, and strive for continuous improvement.  The success of ARKEMA¿s HES programs is reflected by a strong commitment to safety by employees and contractors.  

ARKEMA¿s HES programs include policies, procedures, standards, and guidance materials designed to fulfill ARKEMA¿s commitment to health, environment, and safety.  These materials include Risk Management Program guidance to help our facilities prevent and or reduce the risk of accidents.  

The ARKEMA Carrollton facility is located at 2316 Highland Ave., Carrollton, Kentucky.  The facility is a specialty chemical manufacturer.  Certain substances used and produced

within the facility are regulated under 40 CFR Part 68, the EPA Risk Management Program (RMP) Rule.  Chlorine and methyl chloride are present in covered processes at or above the minimum threshold for RMP applicability.

Chlorine and methyl chloride are used as process feedstocks. Phosphorous Trichloride (PCL3) was reported in the original RMP submittal in 1999. Since that time, the plant has discontinued the product made with PCL3 and no longer stores or processes this chemical. 

The worst-case accidental release scenario is a catastrophic failure of a liquid chlorine rail car.  It should be noted that both regulatory agencies and ARKEMA believe that the worst case scenario is an extremely unlikely event.  This Risk Management Plan includes information on mitigation and prevention measures implemented by ATOFINA to reduce the risk of this type of event.  

The multiple layers of preventative measures make it unlikely that a significant chlorine release will occur.  Chlorine rail cars are built with extreme integrity and safety precautions.  The rail cars are rigorously designed and tested according to the procedures and schedules recommended by the Chlorine Institute.

In addition, in the unlikely event that a release occurs, ARKEMA has an array of mitigation measures to reduce any potential impacts.   These include:

¿ Site emergency action plan;
¿ Chlorine detectors;
¿ Alarm system initiated by chlorine detectors;
¿ Plant emergency alarm system;
¿ Operators trained to make an initial response;
¿ On-site emergency response team for each shift trained at the Hazardous Materials (Haz-Mat) technician level;
¿ Medical department on-site; 
¿ Notification to LEPC to activate Community Response Plan.
¿ Automatic shutoff valves that may be actuated from either the process control room or remote secuity station.
¿ Automatic shutoff valves that are interlocked to shut upon movement of the railcar.

